  <element name="HY_Catchment" substitutionGroup="hyf:HY_HydroFeature" type="hyf:HY_CatchmentType">
    <annotation>
      <documentation>The Catchment model conceptualizes the hydrologic determination of a catchment through inflow and outflow hydro nexus features with the role of getting flow from a contributing catchment, or providing inflow to a receiving catchment (Figure 25 and Figure 26). Conceptually, each catchment has an outflow hydro nexus, and any hydro nexus has a corresponding catchment, even if catchment and/or hydro nexus may not be present in a particular application. A catchment interacts with upper and lower catchments via associated hydro nexuses, and ultimately contributes flow to the hydro nexus of a containing catchment. The catchment should be understood as the logical link between two hydro nexuses.

The HY_Catchment feature type captures the union of catchment and hydro nexus, and the multiple realizations of the holistic catchment concept. These realizations include both topological realizations, as well as their geometric representation. HY_Catchment may be further specialized with respect to catchment interaction. 

The HY_Catchment feature type (Figure 26) specializes the general HY_HydroFeature type. Through generalization, HY_Catchment inherits the &lt;i&gt;name&lt;/i&gt; property. It carries a &lt;i&gt;code&lt;/i&gt; attribute and the associations: &lt;i&gt;outflow&lt;/i&gt;, &lt;i&gt;inflow&lt;/i&gt;, &lt;i&gt;containingCatchment&lt;/i&gt;, &lt;i&gt;containedCatchment&lt;/i&gt;, &lt;i&gt;conjointCatchment&lt;/i&gt;, &lt;i&gt;upperCatchment&lt;/i&gt;, &lt;i&gt;lowerCatchment&lt;/i&gt;, &lt;i&gt;catchmentRealization&lt;/i&gt;.</documentation>
    </annotation>
  </element>
  <complexType name="HY_CatchmentType">
    <complexContent>
      <extension base="hyf:HY_HydroFeatureType">
        <sequence>
          <element minOccurs="0" name="inflow" type="hyf:HY_HydroNexusPropertyType">
            <annotation>
              <documentation>hydro nexus in terms of an inflow to the receiving catchment. For a dendritic network of catchments, the outflow of a contributing catchment coincides with the inflow to a receiving catchment. This supports description of upstream-downstream relationships between catchments.</documentation>
              <appinfo>
                <reversePropertyName xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/gml/3.2">hyf:receivingCatchment</reversePropertyName>
              </appinfo>
            </annotation>
          </element>
          <element minOccurs="0" name="outflow" type="hyf:HY_HydroNexusPropertyType">
            <annotation>
              <documentation>hydro nexus in terms of an outflow of the contributing catchment. For a dendritic network of catchments, the outflow of a contributing catchment coincides with the inflow to a receiving catchment. This supports description of upstream-downstream relationships between catchments.</documentation>
              <appinfo>
                <reversePropertyName xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/gml/3.2">hyf:contributingCatchment</reversePropertyName>
              </appinfo>
            </annotation>
          </element>
          <element maxOccurs="unbounded" name="containedCatchment" type="hyf:HY_CatchmentPropertyType">
            <annotation>
              <documentation>catchment nested in a containing catchment.</documentation>
              <appinfo>
                <reversePropertyName xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/gml/3.2">hyf:containingCatchment</reversePropertyName>
              </appinfo>
            </annotation>
          </element>
          <element minOccurs="0" name="containingCatchment" type="hyf:HY_CatchmentPropertyType">
            <annotation>
              <documentation>catchment nesting contained catchments.</documentation>
              <appinfo>
                <reversePropertyName xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/gml/3.2">hyf:containedCatchment</reversePropertyName>
              </appinfo>
            </annotation>
          </element>
          <element maxOccurs="unbounded" minOccurs="0" name="catchmentRealization" type="hyf:HY_CatchmentRealizationPropertyType">
            <annotation>
              <documentation>topological or geographic feature which realizes the logical catchment.</documentation>
              <appinfo>
                <reversePropertyName xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/gml/3.2">hyf:realizedCatchment</reversePropertyName>
              </appinfo>
            </annotation>
          </element>
          <element maxOccurs="unbounded" minOccurs="0" name="lowerCatchment" type="hyf:HY_CatchmentPropertyType">
            <annotation>
              <documentation>catchment located immediately below of the catchment,</documentation>
              <appinfo>
                <reversePropertyName xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/gml/3.2">hyf:upperCatchment</reversePropertyName>
              </appinfo>
            </annotation>
          </element>
          <element maxOccurs="unbounded" minOccurs="0" name="upperCatchment" type="hyf:HY_CatchmentPropertyType">
            <annotation>
              <documentation>catchment located immediately above of the catchment,</documentation>
              <appinfo>
                <reversePropertyName xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/gml/3.2">hyf:lowerCatchment</reversePropertyName>
              </appinfo>
            </annotation>
          </element>
          <element maxOccurs="unbounded" minOccurs="0" name="conjointCatchment" type="hyf:HY_CatchmentPropertyType">
            <annotation>
              <documentation>catchment that interacts with the catchment across an internal boundary line.</documentation>
            </annotation>
          </element>
          <element minOccurs="0" name="code" type="gml:CodeWithAuthorityType">
            <annotation>
              <documentation>unique identifier to the catchment in given context. The code attribute should be implemented using a controlled classification or coding system. Example: WMO Basin Codes.</documentation>
            </annotation>
          </element>
        </sequence>
      </extension>
    </complexContent>
  </complexType>
